{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dcbd10b7-ff18-4cc1-964a-8267af09f159","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Microsoft identity platform | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Windows auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic Web API with JWT bearer auth (Individual)\ndotnet new webapi --auth Individual -o MyApi\n\n# Azure AD / Entra ID integration\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.com -o MyApi\n```\n\nAdd `--use-minimal-apis` for minimal API style, or `--use-controllers` for controller-based. Run `dotnet new webapi --help` for full options.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d8827d26-6ea3-493b-a7bd-eba0208bc1a4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":274,"requestId":"480E:1FFE72:F2644:120784:69EABD74"},"id":"f7ac096c-e019-48bf-94db-6f06b9f48b6c","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:46:52.800Z","parentId":"2403b918-cc42-4dff-b8ee-d7141c1dc8a2"}
